<subSubSection lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="91" pageId="13" pageNumber="90" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="13" pageNumber="90">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="91" pageId="13" pageNumber="90">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Macrocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Macrocheilus sinuatilabris" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuatilabris">Macrocheilus sinuatilabris</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Macrocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Macrocheilus quadratus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadratus">Macrocheilus quadratus</taxonomicName>
in having three pairs of setae on the labrum and small elytral spots. However, it differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Macrocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Macrocheilus quadratus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadratus">Macrocheilus quadratus</taxonomicName>
in having 
<pageBreakToken pageId="14" pageNumber="91" start="start">smaller</pageBreakToken>
elytral spots, the median tooth of the mentum obtuse at its apex, the rounded apex of the labrum, the close positioning of front and intermediate labral setae, and the slender median lobe of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
